{
  "doc_id": "35992",
  "text": "In many cases (including Greek case), public administrations carry out recruitment after assessing the formal qualifications of candidates. According to Sullivan, 2002 (as stated in the [CITATION_1] ) this system may exclude candidates who do not possess the necessary qualifications but demonstrate exceptional performance in past positions. Candidates should be assessed on the basis of the criteria of the position and less emphasis should be placed on formal qualifications wherever possible. In this manner, candidates who will be able to carry out very effectively the duties they will undertake but do not hold the formal qualifications will not be excluded. Every country places weigh and focus on different elements during the recruitment procedures. Countries such as France, Greece and Spain place weight on education and the results of recruitment competitions. In contradiction to that, countries such as United Kingdom and Sweden place emphasis on work experience and on specialized recruitment competitions. (Aspridis, 2012· Human Resources Management Working Party, 2004 .",
